-
-**4. Applying the Method. A Worked Example**
-
-The six case studies above each applied the three-step method from Section 2, but they applied it implicitly, woven into ordinary paragraphs rather than labeled as steps. This section applies the method explicitly, one step at a time, to an issue outside those six, in order to demonstrate something the case studies alone cannot. that the method itself, rather than any particular topic, is the actual contribution of this paper.
-
-The issue chosen here is deliberately unlike the previous six. It involves no tax office, no border, no police force, no court, and no government category at all. It is the allocation of water between upstream and downstream users during a period of scarcity, a problem that predates every government system discussed so far in this paper, and one that will remain relevant for as long as people live along the same rivers and share the same limited supply.
-
-**Step one. name the values in tension.** A landowner with access to a river has a claim rooted in freedom, the right to use water on their own property as they see fit, without needing permission for ordinary decisions. The wider community along that same river has a claim rooted in security, the need for a supply reliable enough to survive a dry season without collapse. And every user downstream has a claim rooted in equality, since their access to water depends entirely on decisions made by users upstream of them, a matter of geography rather than effort, need, or merit.
-
-**Step two. identify what each position protects and risks.** A position that leaves water use largely unrestricted protects a real and important freedom, the ability to farm, raise animals, or otherwise use one's own land without external interference in routine decisions, and it protects the basic principle that property rights should mean something in practice, not only on paper. Its risk becomes visible only during scarcity. upstream users, acting entirely within their legal rights, can use enough water that little or nothing reliably reaches those downstream, without a single rule being broken by anyone. A position that imposes shared, managed allocation, quotas, permits, or rationing during dry periods, protects a reliable supply for the entire watershed and protects equal standing among users regardless of where their land happens to sit. Its risk is that it requires upstream users to give up a freedom they previously held without question, and it depends entirely on whatever authority manages the allocation doing so competently and fairly. A poorly run allocation system does not remove unfairness. It simply relocates it.
-
-**Step three. ask who bears the cost.** Under unrestricted use, the cost falls on downstream users, and it falls hardest during clearly the moments, drought, scarcity, low rainfall years, when the cost matters most. This is not a punishment for anything they did. It is a consequence of geography alone. Under managed allocation, the cost falls on upstream users, who must now share a resource they could once use without asking, and potentially on the entire watershed if the managing authority allocates poorly, since mismanagement or favoritism in the allocation process introduces a second unfairness on top of the first.
-
-Notice what has happened across these three steps. Without referencing taxation, immigration, policing, criminal justice, inheritance, or identity, a genuinely different domain, one with no institutions, no enforcement, and no written history of government policy at all, has produced the specific same underlying shape. two legitimate values in real conflict, two positions each protecting something true and risking something true, and a cost that lands unevenly no matter which position is chosen. The phrase from Section 2 applies here with unusual precision. A rule stated as "use what is legally yours" is entirely neutral in its wording. Its outcome depends entirely on where a person's land happens to sit along the river, a fact the rule's wording never mentions and was never designed to address.
-
-This is the paper's actual claim, stated as plainly as possible. The six case studies are examples of the method. This seventh is evidence that the method does not depend on its examples.
-
