-**5. Conclusion**
-
-Seven examples have now been examined. taxation, national borders, law enforcement, criminal justice, inheritance, personal identity, and the allocation of river water between neighbors who did not choose where their land happens to sit. Six of these examples involve institutions built over centuries. One involves no institution at all. All seven produced the same underlying shape once the three-step method was applied. two or more legitimate values in genuine conflict, positions on each side protecting something real and risking something real, and a cost that lands unevenly no matter which position prevails.
-
-This paper has not argued that any one of the four values, freedom, security, equality, or order, deserves to win these conflicts in general. It has argued something narrower, and more useful. that most of these disagreements are not contests between people who care about fairness and people who do not, and that treating them that way makes every one of them harder to resolve honestly. A person who weights security highly because they have experienced its absence is not blind to freedom. A person who weights equality highly because they have experienced a rule's unequal outcome is not blind to order. They are reasoning carefully from real experience toward a value that genuinely matters. The disagreement between them deserves to be met with the same three questions each time. which values are actually in tension, what does each position protect and risk, and who bears the cost.
-
-This paper will not go further and recommend which position should win any of the seven debates it has examined. That is a deliberate choice, not a missing chapter. On genuine value conflicts, where the answer depends on how a society weighs freedom against equality, or security against order, there is no fact available to settle the matter the way a fact can settle a dispute about what year something happened. There is only a decision a community makes, together, and continues to make, since the decision rarely stays settled for long.
-
-What can be said, honestly and without pretending to more certainty than the evidence supports, is something about the shape of arrangements that tend to survive contact with reality, regardless of which value they lean toward. Three patterns recur across all seven examples in this paper. Durable arrangements tend to revisit their own terms periodically, rather than treating a single decision as permanent, since circumstances that justified a choice years ago rarely hold unchanged forever. Durable arrangements tend to make their costs visible rather than hidden, since a cost that erodes quietly, a welfare floor that loses real value while its number stays fixed, a rule that is neutral in wording but concentrated in outcome, tends to produce a sharper crisis later clearly because no one was watching it accumulate. And durable arrangements tend to end up as genuine blends rather than pure extremes, since a pure extreme concentrates its entire cost onto one group with no relief, and a system that offers no relief to the people bearing its cost eventually loses their consent to be governed by it.
-
-None of this tells a reader what to conclude about taxation, or borders, or water rights, or any of the other questions this paper has raised. It was never meant to. What it offers instead is a way of staying honest while the argument continues, since for all seven issues examined here, and for whatever seventh, eighth, or hundredth issue eventually replaces them, the argument will continue. The four values do not resolve. They only ever get weighed again, by the next generation, under new circumstances, using whatever method they were given to think it through clearly.
